Explanation:
The solution uses a recursive approach to find the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the two strings. It checks for base cases where either string is empty or has only one character. If the first characters of both strings are equal, it recursively calls the function with the remaining characters of both strings. If the first characters are not equal, it recursively calls the function with the remaining characters of the larger string and the rest of the smaller string. This approach ensures that the function stops when one of the strings becomes shorter than the other, resulting in a time complexity of O(min(n, m)), where n and m are the lengths of the strings. The space complexity is O(1) since the function only uses a constant amount of space. The energy implications are low since the algorithm only performs a few comparisons and recursive calls.

